snippet.textDisplay: So let me get this straight: you're upset that Taylormade has produced a driver that you can swing 0.4 mph faster than the previous model, which equates to about a 1% difference from last years model. With an efficiency of 1.41 on your shots, that 0.4 mph of club head speed equates approximately to a .56 mph jump in ball speed. Take the average and percentage for error and you have a driver that is approximately 19% more consistent than the previous model. This is a year jump and companies R&D departments are thoroughly limited by the USGA and R&A in order to prevent massive jumps in performance. The issue you have is not with the driver's performance but rather Taylormade's marketing scheme which has 0 input into the driver makeup. Love ya Rick, but you continue to intertwine the marketing schemes of a company with research and development.

snippet.textDisplay:
Rick, I do like the way you review as comparing your optimal stats (which I’m sure/hope you have a way of consistently updating) gives us a bench mark on the improvements in technology - however there are some issues I have that don’t make logical/scientific sense to me.
Firstly we know there’s an official ruling on the speed in which the ball can come off the club face, unless this changes how can a driver be “longer” than its previous model - or any model in fact with the maximum COR? I understand how technology can improve to spread the COR to maximise distance on off centre hits, but no matter what technology is in the club it cannot exceed 0.83.
So my second point is your entire review and most of your driver reviews are based on “swinging the club faster” therefore please explain to me how swinging the club faster can increase distance — because after all as mentioned it cannot come off the face faster so how will any driver year on year increase distance with an optimal hit because of the legal parameters and therefore surely making the whole “swing it faster” irrelevant? Because every review of a driver I’ve seen you make in the last years the carry/total distance has been virtually identical to your optimal stats.
In other words how is any driver you review ever going to effect the distance of the shot and what relevance has the whole “swing it faster” got to do with anything while legal parameters restrict any actual changes to a driver performance?
To me any spiel the manufacturer’s use mean nothing including the whole swing it faster term other than to con and manipulate users to buying the club - and of course giving the likes of yourself to make money spinning reviews. I’m not having a dig there, I’m merely suggesting that other than improving stats on mis-hits any term or marketing strategy they use cannot make a difference to hitting the ball further - including “swing it faster”
A response would be much appreciated

snippet.textDisplay: The last thing you should be worrying about is losing a golf ball.  That paranoia causes tension and therefore you're much more likely to lose the ball by hitting it off-line.  When you don't give a s#!t about the ball you're able to give it a free swing and crush it down the middle.  I can't tell you how many people I've seen pull out a new ball and blast it straight OB, then take out an old ball and crush it.  It's the paranoia of losing the new ball that causes the problem.  If you care to much about the ball, don't play that ball!  You have to, not care about the ball, in order to swing freely.  This is one of the reasons everyone hits the ball so much better at the range.  No one is ever worried about losing the ball at the range.

snippet.textDisplay: settings with tm.  10.5 standard..if you put it into 9 degrees the face is open by 3 degrees..so when you square it up..the loft will become stronger than 9..more like 6 degrees..the opposite happens when you up the loft..it closes the face......so rick the 9 degree driver that you set at 7 degrees was more like five when you squared it up at address....the only good thing with tm and titleist is that you can put it more upright..but only in the standard setting..so this will also tend to turn the ball over more and cut out slicing if you are a slicer..id drather have the cobra settings as that doesnt open and close the face..7 means 7

snippet.textDisplay: Do we really need a "new" driver every year. Back when Callaway first came on the market with their Big Bertha and Taylor Made had their Burner range each Driver was around for several years and replaced when there was a genuine leap forward to be made eg The Great Big Bertha and The Bubble TI ranges, both were a leap from steel to Titanium.  Yes the prices went up from around £150 to £300 but future models stayed around this price point.  Now we get a new slightly  different iteration each year and this given the R&D involved (along with the vast sums paid to pros to use the equipment) has moved the price point up to around £500. Surely a move back to greater intervals for introducing  new drivers will see a better return on investment by the manufacturers, lower prices for normal players who simply don't want to or cant afford to swap each year.
snippet.textOriginal: Do we really need a "new" driver every year. Back when Callaway first came on the market with their Big Bertha and Taylor Made had their Burner range each Driver was around for several years and replaced when there was a genuine leap forward to be made eg The Great Big Bertha and The Bubble TI ranges, both were a leap from steel to Titanium.  Yes the prices went up from around £150 to £300 but future models stayed around this price point.  Now we get a new slightly  different iteration each year and this given the R&D involved (along with the vast sums paid to pros to use the equipment) has moved the price point up to around £500. Surely a move back to greater intervals for introducing  new drivers will see a better return on investment by the manufacturers, lower prices for normal players who simply don't want to or cant afford to swap each year.
